     { 0x02, 0x5678, 0xEFEFEFEF },
     ...
   };
   ```

2. Next, you need to determine where the table will be located in flash memory. 

   To do this, you can use a linker script for your project that specifies the memory layout of the microcontroller. You would set aside a portion of the flash memory for your table.

3. Then, you would copy the entire updated table into a temporary buffer in RAM. 

   You would make modifications to the updated table in the RAM buffer.

4. Next, you would erase the corresponding sector of flash memory where the table is located.

   You can use `HAL_FLASH_Erase` function from STM32 HAL library to erase the corresponding sector.

5. Finally, you would write the updated table data to the erased flash memory.

   You can use `HAL_FLASH_Program` function from STM32 HAL library to write the updated table data to the erased flash memory.

Note that updating a table in flash memory requires careful consideration of memory boundaries and flash wear. Therefore, it is important to follow the best practices outlined in the STM32L072 data sheets and documentation, as well as good software engineering practices.

Here is some example C code that demonstrates how to update a table in flash memory on an STM32L072 microcontroller:

```c
#include "stm32l072xx.h"

typedef struct
{
  uint8_t variable1;
  uint16_t variable2;
  uint32_t variable3;
} myTableStruct;

// Define the table in a specific location in flash memory
__attribute__((section(".myTableSection"))) myTableStruct myTable[] =
{
  { 0x01, 0x1234, 0xABCDABCD },
  { 0x02, 0x5678, 0xEFEFEFEF },
  // ...
};

int main(void)
{
  // Define an updated table
  myTableStruct updatedTable[] =
  {
    { 0x01, 0x1234, 0x12345678 },  // Modify variable3 in the first element
    { 0x02, 0x5678, 0x87654321 },
    // ...
  };

  // Calculate the size of the updated table
  size_t updatedTableSize = sizeof(updatedTable);

  // Copy the updated table into a temporary buffer
  uint8_t buffer[updatedTableSize];
  memcpy(buffer, updatedTable, updatedTableSize);

  // Unlock the flash memory for writing
  HAL_FLASH_Unlock();

  // Erase the sector where the table is located
  FLASH_Erase_Sector(FLASH_SECTOR_3, VOLTAGE_RANGE_3);

  // Get the start address of the flash memory location for the table
  uint32_t flashTableAddress = (uint32_t)&myTable;

  // Write the updated table to flash memory
  for (size_t i = 0; i < updatedTableSize; i += 2)
  {
    uint16_t data = buffer[i] | (buffer[i+1] << 8);
    HAL_FLASH_Program(FLASH_TYPEPROGRAM_HALFWORD, flashTableAddress + i, data);
  }

  // Lock the flash memory
  HAL_FLASH_Lock();

  // ...
}
```

